english:
  title: Postscript to the Poetry Collection of Master Geupam
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: 'Years ago, I wrote a preface to the poems of Master Geupam, the maternal grandfather of the Kim brothers. Now, finding myself at the National Academy with Gyeongji, I have come to admire him greatly whenever we meet. In his spare moments after teaching his students, he withdraws to a quiet place and writes a page each day—never ceasing even in the height of summer. This devotion has only deepened my respect for him. It is no wonder: raised in his mother''s household, he harbored a special reverence for his grandfather; and possessed of a natural love for letters and learning, he could not abandon such work. Scarcely had the copying been completed when Yi Dangong, a disciple of Master Geupam who was inspecting Gyeongsang Province, undertook the carving of woodblocks for printing. Thus was the work brought to completion—surely Heaven itself blessed Gyeongji''s filial devotion. As for his younger brother, he ventured into the Central Kingdom, presenting a memorial to the military headquarters of the Prince of Henan, and received high commendation. He was appointed Counselor-in-Waiting and Minister of War in the Chancellery, concurrent overseer of the Privy Council for Henan and regions beyond the Yangtze. Upon his return home, he was, most unhappily, taken by death. Gyeongji has since changed his name to Guyong and has been promoted to the rank of Minister of Revenue, though he retains his teaching position as before.'
  footnotes:
    - Geupam (急菴) was the sobriquet of the maternal grandfather of the Kim brothers; his given name and dates are not specified in this text.
    - The National Academy (成均館, Seongggyungwan) was the highest educational institution in Goryeo and early Joseon.
    - The titles granted to Gyeongji's brother represent significant official positions in Yuan Dynasty China, reflecting the family's prominence.
